<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-528-017  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 528 017.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 21 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC approves price caps for Bell companies. (U.S. FederalCommunications Commission, Bell Regional Holding Companies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesPricing PolicyUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionTelephone companiesGovernment RegulationGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FCC APPROVES PRICE CAPS FOR BELL COMPANIES WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990 SEP21 (NB) -- As expected, the Federal Communications Commission approved asystem of price caps, replacing rate regulation for the nation's Belloperating companies.andP;  The move had been planned for months, and follows asimilar move on behalf of ATandamp;T.andM;The decision will have little practical impact.andP;  Local Bell companies cannotcarry long distance calls, either between states or within states.andP;  However,they do carry a portion of every long distance call, as explained by SouthernBell spokesman William McCloskey.andP;  &quot;When you call Birmingham from Atlanta,the call first goes to your local switch, then to the switch of along-distance company like MCI.andP;  We carry the call between switches andcharge the long-distance company for it.&quot; The same thing happens on the otherend of the call, McCloskey continued, and it's this charge which will fallunder price caps, starting in November, 1991.andM;First, however, there will be one more round of profit regulation, and theallowed rate-of-return on that will be 11.25%, not 12% as previously.andP;  Oncethose charges are determined late this year, the November, 1991 round ofcalculations will be done under the cap.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900921/Press Contact: Dick Miles, Southern Bell,404-529-8003)</TEXT></DOC>